tional name from Bridgford in Staffordshire, or East or West Bridgford in Nottinghamshire, and possibly Bridgeford in Northumberland, which are all named with Old English <i>brycg</i> ‘bridge’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","Scottish: habitational name probably from a lost or unidentified place in Kincardineshire or Aberdeenshire, where the surname is most frequent."],"variants":[{"name":"Bridgforth","meanings":["English: variant of   Bridgeford  ."]},{"name":"Bridgeforth","meanings":["Scottish: probably a variant of the habitational name   Bridgeford  ."]},{"name":"Bridgford","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire): variant of   Bridgeford  ."]}]},{"name":"Bertha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of a Continental Germanic name, a short form of various compound women's personal names derived from <i>berht</i> ‘famous’ (akin to Modern English <i>bright</i>). It probably existed in England before the Conquest, and was certainly reinforced by Norman use, but fell out of use in the 15th century. It was reintroduced into the English-speaking world from Germany in the 19th century, but has once again gone out of fashion."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":1,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":11,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":21,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Bertha de Bridgeford was born on 1 August 1084, in East Bridgford, Nottinghamshire, England. She married Sir Henry de Bisset about 1100, in Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 4 February 1124, in Holderness, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1 August 1084–4 February 1124":"1. august 1084–4. veebruar 1124","1080–1120":"1080–1120","1106–1186":"1106–1186","1084–1124":"1084–1124","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1124":"1124","1186":"1186","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1 February 1120":"1. veebruar 1120","1096":"1096","1 August 1084":"1. august 1084","1084":"1084","about 1100":"umbes 1100","4 February 1124":"4. veebruar 1124","Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England":"Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England","East Bridgford, Nottinghamshire, England":"East Bridgford, Nottinghamshire, England","Holderness, Yorkshire, England, UK":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England","Holderness, Yorkshire, England":"Holderness, Yorkshire, England","Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1 August 1084–4 February 1124":"1. elokuuta 1084–4. helmikuuta 1124","1080–1120":"1080–1120","1106–1186":"1106–1186","1084–1124":"1084–1124","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1124":"1124","1186":"1186","1120":"1120","1086":"1086","1 February 1120":"1. helmikuuta 1120","1096":"1096","1 August 1084":"1. elokuuta 1084","1084":"1084","about 1100":"noin 1100","4 February 1124":"4. helmikuuta 1124","Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England":"Kidderminster, Worcestershire, England","East Bridgford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Ea